imal training, they were impractical for real-world deployment due to large hardware requirements, computational cost, and sensitivity to noise. Later efforts reduced hardware complexity, with [ 9 ] using six arrays and [ 32 ] using two four-channel arrays; however, they still assumed known array geometry and user position. In contrast, single compact devices with small embedded arrays are more aligned with practical applications. More recently, machine learning approaches have been explored. [ 26 ] proposed a hidden Markov model using single-channel audio, though with limited performance compared to multichannel methods. Extensions based on phase coefficients of the cross-power spectrum [ 27 ] were adapted from loudspeaker localization and remained noise sensitive. The work in [ 3 ] predicted eight discrete orientations using a decision tree trained on spectral balance, reverberation, autocorrelation, and GCC-PHAT-based features. Soundr [ 31 ] collected 700 minutes of data and trained a CNN+LSTM on raw 16-channel audio. Despite these advances, Soundr reported a mean orientation error of 57° on unseen speakers and rooms, highlighting the ongoing challenge of achieving robust generalization. Previous approaches have either relied on hand-crafted features based on sound source-to-receiver propagation models [ 3 , 28 , 26 ] or on raw multichannel audio inputs [ 31 ] . Handcrafted features may discard useful information, while raw waveforms require learning representations from scratch, increasing data demands, and overfitting risk. In this work, we propose a novel approach that uses the phase component of the short-time Fourier transform (STFT) as the primary input feature for a deep neural network that combines convolutional, recurrent, and self-attention layers. Unlike lower-dimensional features or raw audio, our method provides richer directional information without requiring the model to learn feature extraction entirely from limited data. Although STFT is widely used in audio processing, its application to orientation estimation has not been explored, likely due to its high dimensionality and corresponding data requirements. To address this, we pre-train on a large simulated dataset generated by leveraging voice directivity patterns (VDP) before fine-tuning on real recordings, achieving state-of-the-art accuracy and strong generalization across speakers and environments. 2 Problem definition and methodology The objective of this work is to estimate the head orientation of a single speaker in the azimuthal plane within a reverberant room environment, using only a single microphone array with specifications similar to those found in smart home audio devices. In this setting, both the speaker and the array may occupy any position within the room at a fixed height, making the task more general and practical compared to methods that assume fixed or calibrated setups. The angle of orientation [MATH] is defined as the angle between the speaker’s facing direction and the line that connects the speaker’s mouth and the center of the microphone array, measured over the full [MATH] – [MATH] range. The system takes a single speech utterance as input and outputs one orientation estimate, assuming static head orientation. Our proposed framework consists of three main components: speech activity detection, feature extraction, and orientation estimation using a deep neural network. Figure 1 illustrates the overall pipeline and the model architecture. Fig. 1 : Head orientation estimation pipeline and model architecture overview. Voice Activity Detection : Non-speech frames may introduce artifacts that confuse the model. To address this, we apply a state-of-the-art voice activity detection module [ 7 ] to filter out leading and trailing non-speech segments. Feature Extraction : For each microphone channel, we compute the STFT using a Hann window with a window size of 4 ms and a stride of 2 ms, and then extract the phase. The short window length follows [ 17 ] , which shows that phase-aware models achieve their best performance in the 2–4 ms regime. To avoid discontinuities at [MATH] , phase is represented by its sine and cosine values [ 17 ] . These features are stacked from all channels along the channel dimension, resulting in an input of size [MATH] , where [MATH] is the number of microphones, [MATH]", "stderr": "", "interrupted": false, "isImage": false, "noOutputExpected": false}}
